    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="157"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.857/355</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 24, 1917</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <persName>Edward Ellis</persName> and <persName>John Handley</persName>, born
                    New York City, have reached London from Falmouth, where landed 20th from British
                    tug <hi rend="italic">Bureaucrat</hi>. Had been picked up in open sea with other
                    members crew of British sailing ship <hi rend="italic">Centurion</hi> after
                    drifting 14 hours. <hi rend="italic">Centurion</hi> left Pensacola, January 1
                    with lumber for London. On February 19, German submarine fired warning shot
                    whereupon crew <pb facs="0319" n="147" xml:id="pg_147"/> took to lifeboats.
                    German seamen placed eight bombs in holds. Vessel sunk within 10 minutes after
                    explosion. Ship unarmed. Crew drifted in fairly heavy sea with limited
                    provisions of food from 11.30 a.m., February 19, until 2.30 following
                    morning.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SRP1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Skinner</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
